<TITLE> Cabinet okays Mobile Court Ordinance </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 28 (bdnews24.com)  The interim cabinet Sunday approved the Mobile Court Ordinance 2007, giving specific judicial powers to executive magistrates. A circular will come out Monday, law adviser Mainul Hosein told bdnews24.com by phone. For the first time in Bangladesh, an ordinance on mobile courts has been approved. The approval came from a meeting of the council of advisers, chaired by chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed at the Chief Adviser's Office. The ordinance lists some jobs like imposing section 144, conducting mobile courts and inspecting examination centres that will be performed by executive magistrates. In case of punishment, the ordinance says the accused cannot be given any other sentence except financial fine, the Press Information Department said in a statement. However, there is a condition that if the fine is not paid voluntarily, the accused can be sentenced to a maximum of three months. If the accused person feels aggrieved by the judgement he can appeal to the sessions judge's court. The decision to allow executive magistrates to have some judicial powers came after a meeting of the leaders of Bangladesh Civil Service Administration Association with the law adviser. bdnews24.c
